71":"1503–1571","1470–Male":"1470–Deceased","1503":"1503","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1473":"1473","1571":"1571","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","England":"England","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Normond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gaston, Andre, Laurent, Marcel, Pierre, Amie, Donat, Emile, Herve, Jacques, Jean Noel, Jean-Michel.","French and Breton (mainly Finistère; also <b>Le Normand</b>): habitational name for someone from Normandy, a region in northern France (see   Norman  ). Compare   Lenormand  .","Scottish (Fife): variant of   Norman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Norman","meanings":["English, Irish (Dublin and Cork), and Scottish: ethnic or habitational name applied either to a Scandinavian or to someone from Normandy in northern France. The Scandinavian adventurers of the Dark Ages called themselves <i>northmenn</i> ‘men from the North’. Before 1066, Scandinavian settlers in England were already fairly readily absorbed, and <i>Northman</i> and <i>Normann</i> came to be used as bynames and later as personal names, even among the Saxon inhabitants. The term gained a new use from 1066 onward, when England was settled by invaders from Normandy, who were likewise of Scandinavian origin but by now largely integrated with the native population and speaking a Romance language, retaining only their original ancient Germanic name.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Norman</i> (recorded in the late Old English period as <i>Northman</i>), derived from <i>northman</i> ‘northerner’.","Americanized form of German   Normann  ."]},{"name":"Normandeau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Marcel.","French: from a diminutive of   Normand  ."]},{"name":"Lormand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Eustache.","Altered form of French   Normand  .","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Le Lormand in the Pyrénées-Atlantique."]},{"name":"Norment","meanings":["Scottish: probably a variant of   Normand  ."]},{"name":"Lenormand","meanings":["French; Breton (Côtes-d'Armor and Morbihan; mainly <b>Le Normand</b>): variant of   Normand  , with the French masculine definite article <i>le</i>."]},{"name":"Normandin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Alain, Serge, Adrien, Andre, Aurore, Celine, Clovis, Emile, Gaetan, Gilles, Laurier.","French: from a diminutive of   Normand  . Compare   Normandy  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":79,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - 